// p72 — Function-body locals shadow module-level globals (v3.13.0).
//
// Before v3.13.0, a top-level `n := "alex"` materialised as an LLVM
// GlobalVariable typed String*. When ANY stdlib method's body did
// `n := self.length()` (e.g. List.sort's inner sort loop), the
// codegen's var-decl path checked `varGen->exists("n")` — which
// returned true thanks to the global — and routed the local
// declaration through `updateLocalVariable`, writing an Int
// (self.length()) through the String*-typed global slot.
// Downstream `i < n` then tripped LLVM's ICmp operand-type
// assertion at IR verification:
//
//   Both operands to ICmp instruction are not of the same type!
//
// The fix is local — inside a function body, a fresh `name := value`
// declaration always allocates a new local that shadows any
// module-level same-named binding. The bug only fired for
// short identifiers (`i`, `j`, `n`) because those happen to
// appear as locals across the stdlib; longer names dodged it
// by accident.
//
// Probe trips the original repro: a top-level `n := <String>`
// followed by any code that touches a stdlib method using `n`
// internally. Without the v3.13.0 fix the program ICEs before
// printing anything; with the fix both the global and the
// method-local read their declared types cleanly.

n := "alex"
print(n)                              // = alex

// Touch List.sort which has `n := self.length()` in its body.
// Pre-v3.13.0 this caused the LLVM verifier to abort at compile
// time, before any code ran. Post-fix the inner `n` is a local
// scoped to sort()'s frame and doesn't disturb the global.
xs := [3, 1, 2]
xs.sort(fn(a: Int, b: Int) => a - b)
print(xs)                             // = [1, 2, 3]

// Confirm the top-level `n` retained its String value through
// the sort call.
print(n)                              // = alex
print(n.length())                     // = 4
